Welcome to notebook seven of the Java track. This is the last pure Java notebook before we pivot to Spring. The topic for this session is the runtime and the tooling that wraps everything we have built so far. We will look at the java virtual machine itself. How class loading works. How reflection lets your code inspect other code at runtime. How annotations and reflection together form the substrate that Spring uses. And the practical scaffolding that every real Java project has. Build tools, namely Maven and Gradle. And the testing stack, namely JUnit five and Mockito.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, the java virtual machine. Its runtime memory layout, with the heap, the per thread stacks, and the metaspace. Garbage collection in one breath, including the generational hypothesis and the three modern collectors. Class loading, and how a class file on disk becomes a live class in memory. The Java platform module system in sixty seconds. Then annotations and reflection. Writing your own annotation type with the meta annotations target and retention. The reflection application programming interface for inspecting and invoking classes, methods, and fields. The pattern of reading annotations via reflection, which is the bridge to Spring. Then the build tools. Maven, with its declarative pom dot xml file. Gradle, with its script based build dot gradle file, and when each tool wins. Finally, the testing stack. JUnit five, with its at sign Test annotation, lifecycle hooks, assertions, and parameterised tests. Mockito, with the mock, when, and verify trio for behaviour based tests.

Let us start with the java virtual machine. When you launch a Java program with the java command, the java virtual machine starts up and creates a fixed set of runtime memory regions. The three you should know are the heap, the per thread stacks, and the metaspace.

The heap is where every Java object lives. The heap is shared across all threads, and it is managed by the garbage collector. Whenever you write new, somewhere in your code, the resulting object is allocated on the heap.

The stack is one per thread. Each thread has its own stack. The stack holds local variables, method parameters, and the call chain. Every method call pushes a new stack frame, which holds that method's locals and a return address. When the method returns, its frame is popped, and the locals are gone. The stack is small, typically half a megabyte, which is why deeply recursive code throws stack overflow error.

The metaspace holds class metadata. The bytecode for each method. The tables of methods and fields. The class objects themselves, which we will meet in a moment when we get to reflection. Metaspace replaced the older permanent generation, or perm gen, in Java eight. Unlike perm gen, metaspace grows dynamically by default, so the old class metadata out of memory error is largely a thing of the past.

One distinction worth registering now. Primitives declared as local variables live on the stack, inline. Objects, including the boxed wrappers like Integer, always live on the heap. The local variable on the stack just holds a reference, essentially a pointer, to the heap object.

Garbage collection in one breath. The java virtual machine tracks which heap objects are reachable from your live code, starting from local variables, static fields, and a handful of other root sets. Any object the garbage collector cannot reach is, by definition, garbage. The collector reclaims its memory. You never call free in Java.

The generational hypothesis is the assumption every modern garbage collector builds on. It says that most objects die young. The vast majority of allocations are short lived. To exploit this, the heap is split into a young generation and an old generation. New objects are born in the young generation. Collections of the young generation are cheap, because most objects are already dead by the time a collection runs. Objects that survive several young generation collections get promoted to the old generation. Collections of the old generation happen less often, and they are more expensive.

You do not tune garbage collection unless something specific forces you to. The defaults are good. When you do need to tune, the three modern collectors worth knowing are G one, Z G C, and Shenandoah. G one is the default since Java nine. It targets mostly short pauses, with a reasonable balance between throughput and latency. It is the right choice for most workloads. Z G C is a sub millisecond pause collector designed for very large heaps and latency sensitive services. Shenandoah is similar to Z G C in design and pause characteristics. It is favoured in the open J D K distribution from Red Hat. You select a collector with a java virtual machine flag. Use G one G C. Use Z G C. Use Shenandoah G C.

Now class loading. A class file on disk is not useful to the java virtual machine until a class loader reads it and makes it available as a Class object. Three class loaders work in delegation. The bootstrap loader, which is the lowest level loader, handles the core java development kit classes, like everything in java dot lang and java dot util. The platform loader handles the rest of the java development kit modules. The application loader handles your application's classpath. And you can write custom loaders on top, which is what frameworks and application servers do.

Class loading is lazy. A class is loaded the first time it is referenced in the running program. This laziness is exactly why Spring's classpath scanning works the way it does. Spring walks every class file it can find on the classpath, asks the loader to load each one, and then uses reflection to look at the result.

You almost never write a custom class loader. But the delegation chain explains a class of bugs you might encounter. When two different class loaders load the same class file, the java virtual machine treats the resulting classes as different types. A cast between them throws class cast exception, even though the names match exactly. If you ever see this in a complex application server environment, you now know what is happening.

A sixty second tour of the Java module system. Java nine introduced the module system, sometimes called J P M S. A module is a named bundle of packages that explicitly declares which packages it exports and which other modules it requires. A module is described by a file called module dash info dot java, placed at the root of the module's source.

Inside the module info, the requires keyword declares a dependency on another module. The exports keyword declares that a package is visible to consumers. Packages that are not exported are module private. They cannot be referenced from outside the module, even if they are public in the older sense.

Most application code, especially Spring Boot services, does not use the module system directly. Spring Boot still ships as classpath jar files. The module system matters mainly in three places. When you are building a library that wants strong encapsulation against its users. When you are using the j link tool to ship a slimmed down java runtime environment containing only the modules your application uses. And when you are maintaining the java development kit itself. For day to day Spring work, treat the module system as background knowledge.

Now, annotations and reflection. These are the two ideas that, together, make Spring possible. Notebook two introduced the built in annotations, like at sign Override, at sign Deprecated, and at sign Suppress Warnings. Now we go deeper. We will write our own annotation type, and we will learn the meta annotations that control where and when the annotation is visible.

To declare a custom annotation, you use the at sign interface keyword, followed by a name. So at sign interface Audited declares a new annotation type called Audited. Inside the body, you can declare attributes, which look like methods with no body and an optional default value. So String value default empty string is an attribute called value, with a default of an empty string. String array tags default empty array is an attribute called tags, with a default of an empty array.

Then you control the annotation with two meta annotations. At sign Target takes one or more element types and restricts where the annotation can be applied. The most common element types are TYPE, for classes and interfaces. METHOD, for methods. FIELD, for fields. PARAMETER, for method parameters. CONSTRUCTOR, for constructors. And several others. At sign Retention takes a retention policy that controls how long the annotation is kept. The three retention policies are SOURCE, CLASS, and RUNTIME. Source retention means the annotation is discarded at compile time. Only source level tools, like lint tools, see it. Class retention means the annotation is written to the class file but is not loaded into memory at runtime. This is the default. Runtime retention means the annotation is present at runtime and is readable via reflection.

Critical fact to memorise. If you forget at sign Retention with runtime policy on a custom annotation, reflection will not see it. This is one of the most common bugs when people first write framework style annotations. Always include at sign Retention with retention policy runtime if you intend the annotation to be read at runtime.

Now, reflection. The reflection application programming interface lets your code, at runtime, inspect classes, methods, fields, constructors, and annotations, and invoke them. Everything in reflection starts from a Class object, of type Class of question mark, the wildcard Class type. You can get a Class object three ways.

One. From an instance. Call get Class on any object, and you get back the Class object for its runtime type. Two. From a class literal. Write the class name, then dot class. So String dot class is the Class object for String. Three. From a name. Call Class dot for Name with the fully qualified class name as a string. This is what frameworks use when they discover class names dynamically from the classpath.

Once you have a Class object, you can ask questions about it. The get Name method returns the fully qualified name. The get Simple Name method returns just the last segment. The get Package Name method returns the package. The is Interface method tells you whether it is an interface. The get Super class method returns the Class of the direct superclass. The get Interfaces method returns the array of interfaces it implements.

From a Class object, you can also list and invoke members. The get Declared Methods method returns the array of methods declared directly on the class, ignoring inherited ones. The get Methods method, without declared, returns all public methods including inherited ones. The get Declared Method method, singular, takes a name and a list of parameter types, and returns the matching method.

To invoke a method via reflection, you call the invoke method on the Method object. The first argument is the instance on which to call the method, or null for a static method. The remaining arguments are the method's actual arguments. The invoke method returns the result as Object, which you can cast.

To create an instance of a class via reflection, you find the constructor with get Declared Constructor, then call new Instance on the constructor object.

Reading and writing fields works similarly. The get Declared Field method takes a name and returns a Field object. To read or write a private field, you have to call set Accessible with true on the field, which bypasses Java's normal access control. Then call get on the field to read, or set on the field to write.

Reflection has costs. Reflective calls are slower than direct calls. They bypass compile time type checking, so errors that the compiler would have caught become runtime errors. Reach for reflection only when you need to operate on code that you do not know about until runtime. Framework code processing user supplied classes. A serialiser inspecting fields. A test runner discovering test methods. Not every day application logic.

And now, the punchline of this whole notebook. The bridge to Spring. Reading annotations via reflection is the pattern that powers essentially every Spring feature. The technique uses two application programming interface calls. From a Class object, call get Annotation, passing the Class of the annotation type. If the annotation is present on the class, you get the annotation instance back, and you can read its attribute values. If it is not present, you get null.

For method level annotations, you iterate the declared methods with get Declared Methods, and on each method, call get Annotation with the Class of the annotation type. Same pattern. If present, read its values. If absent, null.

That two step pattern is the seed of Spring. Spring's component scanner does exactly this. It walks the classpath looking for class files. For each one, it calls Class dot for Name to load the class. It calls get Annotation on the resulting Class object, looking for at sign Component, at sign Service, at sign Repository, at sign Controller, or at sign Configuration. When it finds one, it instantiates the class using reflection, wires up its at sign Autowired fields by looking at their types via reflection, and registers the resulting object in the application context. Spring is not magic. It is Class dot for Name, get Annotation, and new Instance, organised at scale.

Now we shift from runtime mechanics to build tooling. Almost every Spring project you encounter uses one of two build tools. Maven or Gradle.

Maven is older, more declarative, and more standardised. The project descriptor is a file called pom dot xml. The acronym pom stands for project object model. Inside the p o m, you declare the group identifier, the artifact identifier, and the version of your project. You declare properties, like the Java release version. You declare dependencies, with their group, artifact, version, and an optional scope like test, which marks a dependency as only needed for testing.

Maven dependencies are resolved transitively from a remote repository, called Maven Central by default. You declare only the libraries you depend on directly. Maven pulls in everything those libraries depend on, recursively.

Maven runs a fixed build lifecycle. Most daily work involves a handful of commands. The m v n compile command compiles your sources. The m v n test command compiles and runs the unit tests. The m v n package command compiles, runs tests, and builds the jar archive. The m v n install command additionally puts the artifact into your local Maven repository, under the dot m two directory in your home folder. The m v n clean command deletes the target directory. And the m v n dependency tree command shows the full transitive dependency graph, which is invaluable for debugging dependency conflicts.

Gradle is the alternative build tool. Gradle uses Groovy or Kotlin as a domain specific language, instead of x m l. The build script lives in a file called build dot gradle, or build dot gradle dot kts for the Kotlin variant. Gradle is faster than Maven on incremental builds, because it caches task outputs aggressively. Gradle is also more flexible, because the build script is a real programming language, so you can express logic that would be cumbersome in declarative x m l. Gradle is the build tool that Spring Boot's own initialisr defaults to today.

Common Gradle commands. The gradlew build command compiles, tests, and packages. The gradlew test command runs the tests. The gradlew boot run command, when the Spring Boot plugin is applied, runs the Spring Boot application directly. The gradlew clean command deletes the build directory. And the gradlew dependencies command shows the dependency graph.

The gradlew script is the Gradle wrapper. A small shim committed alongside your project that downloads the exact Gradle version the project expects. Maven has an equivalent, called the Maven wrapper, invoked as m v n w. Always commit the wrapper script. Never expect contributors to have the right version of the build tool installed globally on their machines.

Maven versus Gradle, in one line. Maven is simpler and standard. Gradle is faster and more flexible. New Spring projects increasingly start with Gradle. Older codebases are almost always Maven.

Finally, the testing stack. JUnit five is the standard test runner for Java. A test class is a plain Java class. A test method is any method annotated at sign Test. The runner discovers test methods via reflection. Same mechanism we just covered.

JUnit five also defines lifecycle hooks. The at sign Before Each annotation runs the method before every test. Useful for setting up a fresh instance under test. The at sign After Each annotation runs after every test, useful for cleanup. The at sign Before All annotation runs once before any test in the class. The at sign After All annotation runs once after all tests. The before all and after all hooks must be on static methods.

The assertions you will use ninety percent of the time. The assert Equals method takes an expected value and an actual value. The assert True and assert False methods take a boolean. The assert Null and assert Not Null methods take a reference. The assert Throws method takes the expected exception class and a runnable, runs the runnable, and asserts that it throws the expected exception, returning the exception instance for further inspection. The assert All method lets you group multiple checks, so all of them are evaluated even if one fails. For more expressive assertions, reach for the assert That style provided by the third party library AssertJ.

When you want to run the same test logic across many inputs, parameterise the test. JUnit five supports several source forms. The at sign Value Source annotation supplies a list of literal values. The at sign C s v Source annotation supplies rows of comma separated values, mapped to the test method's parameters by position. The at sign Method Source annotation references a static method that returns a stream of arguments. Pick whichever fits your data.

And finally, Mockito. When the code under test depends on something heavy, like a database, a remote service, or the system clock, you do not want the test to actually need that dependency. Mockito lets you substitute a fake implementation that returns whatever you tell it to, and lets you assert which methods on it got called.

The Mockito vocabulary. The static mock method takes a Class and returns a mock instance of that type. All methods on a mock return defaults, namely null, zero, or false, until you stub them. The static when method, combined with then Return, defines what a stubbed call returns. The static when method combined with then Throw defines an exception to throw. The static verify method, applied to a mock, asserts that a specific call was made. The verify method can be combined with never, times of n, or at Least Once to assert call counts. The static any method, and its typed variants like any Long and any String, are argument matchers that match any value of the given type. The static eq method wraps an exact value as an argument matcher, which is needed when mixing matchers with literals.

Mockito works by generating a subclass of the mocked type at runtime, and intercepting every method call to record arguments and produce stubbed responses. Yet another use of reflection, under the hood. The combination of JUnit five plus Mockito plus AssertJ is the test stack you will see in essentially every modern Spring project.

That wraps notebook seven. The Java foundation is now complete. You know what is happening underneath your code. How the java virtual machine lays out memory. How class loading and reflection let frameworks read your code as data. How annotations and reflection together form the substrate that Spring will use to wire your services. You also have the practical scaffolding. Maven or Gradle for builds. JUnit five with Mockito for tests.

Notebook eight begins the Spring journey, with Spring Core. The application context. Dependency injection. Component scanning. The bean lifecycle. Configuration profiles. And aspect oriented programming. Everything you saw in this notebook, especially annotations, reflection, and classpath scanning, will resurface as Spring's machinery for getting your code to talk to itself, with no glue code from you.
